TY  - JOUR
T1  - Is This How I Will Be Treated? Reducing Uncertainty through Recruitment Interactions
AU  - Walker, H. Jack
AU  - Bauer, Talya N.
AU  - Cole, Michael S.
AU  - Bernerth, Jeremy B.
AU  - Feild, Hubert S.
AU  - Short, Jeremy C.
Y1  - 2012/07/19
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2013/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.0196
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2011.0196
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1325
EP  - 1347
VL  - 56
IS  - 5
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - While a great deal of research has investigated strategies for increasing job seekers' initial attraction to organizations, far less is known about how job seekers respond to recruitment activities after application submission. We draw from signaling, uncertainty reduction, and uncertainty management theories to develop a conceptual model of the relationship between recruitment interactions (contact episodes) after application submission and organizational attraction. We test this model in three independent studies with data collected at multiple time periods. Study 1 employed a time-lagged research design with actual job seekers. Findings showed that justice perceptions associated with recruitment interactions influence attraction to an organization indirectly and directly via positive relational certainty (i.e., reduced uncertainty regarding how organizational relations might be upon entering the organization). Study 2 used a controlled experimental design to provide additional evidence of the relational certainty mechanism through which justice signals influence attraction. Finally, Study 3 incorporated a longitudinal (repeated-measures) design to examine reactions to recruitment interactions over ten weeks. Results indicated that the relationship between justice signals and organizational attraction via positive relational certainty is dynamic, suggesting that organizations should carefully manage their communications throughout the recruitment process.
AB  - While a great deal of research has investigated strategies for increasing job seekers' initial attraction to organizations, far less is known about how job seekers respond to recruitment activities after application submission. We draw from signaling, uncertainty reduction, and uncertainty management theories to develop a conceptual model of the relationship between recruitment interactions (contact episodes) after application submission and organizational attraction. We test this model in three independent studies with data collected at multiple time periods. Study 1 employed a time-lagged research design with actual job seekers. Findings showed that justice perceptions associated with recruitment interactions influence attraction to an organization indirectly and directly via positive relational certainty (i.e., reduced uncertainty regarding how organizational relations might be upon entering the organization). Study 2 used a controlled experimental design to provide additional evidence of the relational certainty mechanism through which justice signals influence attraction. Finally, Study 3 incorporated a longitudinal (repeated-measures) design to examine reactions to recruitment interactions over ten weeks. Results indicated that the relationship between justice signals and organizational attraction via positive relational certainty is dynamic, suggesting that organizations should carefully manage their communications throughout the recruitment process.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2011.0196
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amj.2011.0196
Y2  - 2026/04/24
